articles.headline: As World’s Gaze Shifts to Gaza, Israel’s Psyche Remains Defined by Oct. 7 Attack
articles.snippet: Hamas’s brutal raid and taking of hostages has left Israelis deeply traumatized and is expected to reshape the country for years to come.
articles.abstract: Hamas’s brutal raid and taking of hostages has left Israelis deeply traumatized and is expected to reshape the country for years to come.
articles.lead_paragraph: The Oct. 7 attack on Israel has prompted soul-searching on the Israeli left, undermining faith in a shared future with Palestinians. It has created a crisis of confidence on the Israeli right, sapping support for Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. It has drawn ultra-Orthodox Jews, often ambivalent about their relationship to the Israeli state, closer to the mainstream.

articles.headline: A New Tax on Imports and a Split From China: Trump’s 2025 Trade Agenda
articles.snippet: Donald J. Trump plans to sharply expand his use of tariffs if he returns to power, risking disruption to the economy in an attempt to transform it.
articles.abstract: Donald J. Trump plans to sharply expand his use of tariffs if he returns to power, risking disruption to the economy in an attempt to transform it.
articles.lead_paragraph: Former President Donald J. Trump is planning an aggressive expansion of his first-term efforts to upend America’s trade policies if he returns to power in 2025 — including imposing a new tax on “most imported goods” that would risk alienating allies and igniting a global trade war.
articles.byline: By Charlie Savage, Jonathan Swan and Maggie Haberman

articles.headline: In This Mexican Neighborhood, Locals Say ¡Viva el Beetle!
articles.snippet: A northern community in Mexico City cannot give up on the famous 1960s hippie-favorite Volkswagen.
articles.abstract: A northern community in Mexico City cannot give up on the famous 1960s hippie-favorite Volkswagen.
articles.lead_paragraph: Rusted and stripped of their right seat, the cars parked in queues rounding street corners serve as the unofficial taxi in the hillside neighborhoods in Cuautepec in Mexico’s capital. The curvy symbol of the 1960s hippie era is admired — even decorated and named — by residents who say the car represents their resilience and work ethic.
articles.byline: By Zolan Kanno-Youngs and Marian Carrasquero

articles.headline: Downturn or Not? At Year’s End, Wall St. Is Split on What’s Ahead.
articles.snippet: Analysts bullish on 2023 were largely right and expect more of the same in 2024. Bears caution that the Fed’s impact is yet to be determined.
articles.abstract: Analysts bullish on 2023 were largely right and expect more of the same in 2024. Bears caution that the Fed’s impact is yet to be determined.
articles.lead_paragraph: Twelve months ago, Tom Lee bet that 2023 was going to turn out just fine.

articles.headline: Holiday Spending Increased, Defying Fears of a Decline
articles.snippet: While the pace of growth slowed, spending stayed strong because of robust job growth and strong wage gains.
articles.abstract: While the pace of growth slowed, spending stayed strong because of robust job growth and strong wage gains.
articles.lead_paragraph: Despite lingering inflation, Americans increased their spending this holiday season, early data shows. That comes as a big relief for retailers that had spent much of the year fearing the economy would soon weaken and consumer spending would fall.
